The Golgi apparatus operates at the intersection of the secretory, lysosomal, and endocytic pathways." [ISBN:0198506732]

name: embryo development

Signal transduction ends with regulation of a downstream cellular process, e.g. regulation of transcription or regulation of a metabolic process. For signaling between cells, signal transduction is restricted to events at and within the receiving cell." [GOC:go_curators, GOC:mtg_signaling_feb11]

The furrow ingresses until a cytoplasmic bridge is formed." [GOC:kmv, PMID:12707312]

name: regulation of ureter smooth muscle cell differentiation

name: response to estradiol

name: flavin adenine dinucleotide catabolic process

name: metanephric cortical collecting duct development

The metanephric cortical collecting duct is the portion of the metanephric collecting duct that resides in the renal cortex." [GOC:mtg_kidney_jan10]

name: histone H2B-K5 acetylation

name: right lung development
description: "The biological process whose specific outcome is the progression of a right lung from an initial condition to its mature state. This process begins with the formation of the right lung and ends with the mature structure. The right lung is the lung which is on the right side of the anterior posterior axis looking from a dorsal to ventral aspect." [GOC:dph, GOC:mtg_lung]

name: ureteric bud morphogenesis
description: "The process in which the ureteric bud is generated and organized." [GOC:dph, GOC:mtg_kidney_jan10]

name: mesenchymal cell proliferation involved in prostate gland development
description: "The multiplication or reproduction of mesenchymal cells, resulting in the expansion of a cell population that contributes to the progression of the prostate gland over time." [GOC:dph, PMID:12221011]

name: regulation of mesenchymal cell proliferation involved in prostate gland development
description: "Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of mesenchymal cell proliferation that contributes to the progression of the prostate gland over time. A mesenchymal cell is a cell that normally gives rise to other cells that are organized as three-dimensional masses, rather than sheets." [GOC:dph, PMID:12221011]

name: mesenchymal smoothened signaling pathway involved in prostate gland development

name: positive regulation of sclerotome development
description: "Any process that increases the rate, frequency, or extent of the progression of the sclerotome over time, from its initial formation to the mature structure. The sclerotome is the portion of the somite that will give rise to a vertebra." [GOC:BHF, GOC:dph]

name: regulation of sclerotome development
description: "Any process that modulates the rate, frequency, or extent of the progression of the sclerotome over time, from its initial formation to the mature structure. The sclerotome is the portion of the somite that will give rise to a vertebra." [GOC:dph]

name: renal cortex development

name: cortical collecting duct development
description: "The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the cortical collecting duct over time, from its formation to the mature structure. The cortical collecting duct is the portion of the collecting duct that resides in the renal cortex." [GOC:mtg_kidney_jan10]

name: mesonephric tubule morphogenesis

name: kidney smooth muscle cell differentiation

A photoreceptor cell is a cell that responds to incident electromagnetic radiation. Different classes of photoreceptor have different spectral sensitivities and express different photosensitive pigments." [GOC:mtg_sensu]

name: negative regulation of transforming growth factor beta activation

name: regulation of transcription-coupled nucleotide-excision repair
description: "Any process that modulates the frequency, rate, or extent of the nucleotide-excision repair process that carries out preferential repair of DNA lesions on the actively transcribed strand of the DNA duplex. In addition, the transcription-coupled nucleotide-excision repair pathway is required for the recognition and repair of a small subset of lesions that are not recognized by the global genome nucleotide excision repair pathway." [GOC:tb]

name: negative regulation of eye pigmentation

name: regulation of cellular response to stress

Cellular response to stress is a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a stimulus indicating the organism is under stress. The stress is usually, but not necessarily, exogenous (e.g. temperature, humidity, ionizing radiation)." [GOC:dhl]

name: HSP90-CDC37 chaperone complex

The highly conserved, phosphorylated CDC37-Ser13 (vertebrates) or cdc37-Ser14 (yeast) is essential for complex assembly and target protein binding. CDC37-Ser13 (Ser14) is phosphorylated by Casein kinase II (CK2), which in turn is a target of CDC37 creating a positive feedback loop. Complex binding also prevents rapid ubiquitin-dependent proteosomal degradation of target proteins." [GOC:bhm, GOC:pad, GOC:PARL, PMID:21855797, PMID:22939624]

name: VCP-NSFL1C complex

name: negative regulation of lipid storage
